<HEADLINE>
<P>
APPLE EMPLOYEE FIRED FOR LEAKING INFORMATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CUPERTINO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Apple Computer, which fired a programmer for leaking information, has served 
notice that there will be "sanctions" against any employee who breaches its 
security. 
</P>
<P>
David Ramsey, 33, author of Apple's MacPaint 2.0 program, said he was fired 
Thursday for using the CompuServe electronic bulletin board to disclose 
information. 
</P>
<P>
Chris Escher said Monday that Apple has "a commitment to open communication and 
that environment is based on trust. 
</P>
<P>
"All employees have sensitive material in their hands every day, and we expect 
them to act with good judgment regarding that information. Implicit in that 
environment is an agreement that there must be limits and sanctions on people 
who break that trust." 
</P>
<P>
Ramsey said he did not know that the information put out by CompuServe was 
"confidential." He said he believed that it had already been discussed by Apple 
Chairman John Sculley. 
</P>
<P>
Ramsey began working at Apple two years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
