<HEADLINE>
<P>
NRC CHIEF FAULTS NUCLEAR INDUSTRY AS UNCOOPERATIVE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The nuclear industry has not cooperated with the federal government in 
tightening maintenance rules for nuclear power plants, the outgoing head of the 
Nuclear Regulatory Commission said today. 
</P>
<P>
"The nuclear industry should have been more cooperative with us and they were 
not," said Lando Zech, who steps down as NRC chairman Friday after a three-year 
term. 
</P>
<P>
Zech said the state of the nuclear industry as a whole is healthy, but added 
that he was "somewhat disappointed" to have made little progress on tightening 
maintenance standards. 
</P>
<P>
Zech said the nuclear industry, which has not applied to build a new nuclear 
plant in 11 years, faces an uncertain future. 
</P>
<P>
"Nuclear power supplies 20% of U.S. electricity needs safely now, but it's 
impossible to say where we're going," Zech said. "I have no crystal ball." 
</P>
<P>
Zech will be replaced by NRC Commissioner Kenneth Carr. 
</P>
</TEXT>
